1

00:00:01,760  -->  00:00:05,325
Let's imagine you're looking to invest in a home.

2

00:00:05,325  -->  00:00:08,100
In particular, you would like to purchase a home

3

00:00:08,100  -->  00:00:11,115
where you think it's worth more than the listed price.

4

00:00:11,115  -->  00:00:15,475
We collect information on recently sold homes to use in your pursuit.

5

00:00:15,475  -->  00:00:18,185
Here's a table of the information you collect;

6

00:00:18,185  -->  00:00:20,779
the price of the home, the neighborhood,

7

00:00:20,779  -->  00:00:24,080
which has three categories of neighborhoods, A, B,

8

00:00:24,080  -->  00:00:26,960
or C, the square footage of the house,

9

00:00:26,960  -->  00:00:28,475
the number of bedrooms,

10

00:00:28,475  -->  00:00:29,870
the number of bathrooms,

11

00:00:29,870  -->  00:00:33,520
and the style, either ranch, Victorian or lodge.

12

00:00:33,520  -->  00:00:34,970
In the last lesson,

13

00:00:34,970  -->  00:00:36,200
you learned how to use one of

14

00:00:36,200  -->  00:00:39,410
these quantitative columns to predict the price of the house.

15

00:00:39,410  -->  00:00:41,800
But what if we wanted to use all of these?

16

00:00:41,800  -->  00:00:44,900
What about these columns multiplying a slope of

17

00:00:44,900  -->  00:00:48,650
seven by neighborhood A or home style Victorian,

18

00:00:48,650  -->  00:00:50,510
what would that even mean?

19

00:00:50,510  -->  00:00:54,140
It turns out that we can use linear algebra to predict

20

00:00:54,140  -->  00:00:57,760
the y value using all of these inputs at the same time.

21

00:00:57,760  -->  00:01:01,070
The way we do this is by creating a matrix of inputs,

22

00:01:01,070  -->  00:01:02,555
so these values here,

23

00:01:02,555  -->  00:01:05,900
and we create a vector of the response that we want to predict.

24

00:01:05,900  -->  00:01:09,980
This matrix is often denoted as X,

25

00:01:09,980  -->  00:01:13,640
while this vector for the response is denoted with y.

26

00:01:13,640  -->  00:01:16,610
To differentiate from the notation you saw earlier,

27

00:01:16,610  -->  00:01:19,310
each of these generally is notated as bold.

28

00:01:19,310  -->  00:01:21,950
In order to really grasp all of what's

29

00:01:21,950  -->  00:01:24,770
happening with multiple linear regression and how it works,

30

00:01:24,770  -->  00:01:30,210
you need to understand how these vectors and matrices work together.
